Jurors in the McMartin Pre-School molestation case said today that they have reached a 
verdict on 52 counts of the case and remained deadlocked on the last 13 charges.  
Raymond Buckey and his mother, Peggy McMartin Buckey, are charged with 64 counts 
of molestation of children attending their family-owned pre-school and one count of 
conspiracy.  This is the longest, most costly, criminal trial in history.  Superior Court 
Judge William Pounds will hold a hearing on Thursday.  One decision could be opening 
the sealed verdicts.  Jurors, in the ninth week of deliberations, have questioned elements 
of the charges and appeared confused.</SUM>  

<SUM
DOCSET="d080"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP900118-0205"
SELECTOR="A"
SUMMARIZER="I">

The McMartin Pre-School molestation case began in August 1983 when Judy Johnson 
accused Raymond Buckey of molesting her son.  By March 1984, a public outcry had 
been created and seven people were arrested for abusing 18 children over 10 years.  In 
January 1986, the preliminary hearing, after 18 months and $4 million, brought 135 
counts against the seven.  Charges later were dismissed against all but Buckey and his 
mother.  Jury selection began in April 1987 and the actual trial ran from July until 
November 1989.  On January 18, 1990 they were acquitted on 52 counts, with a mistrial 
declared on 13 counts.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d080"
