Thursday's acquittals in the McMartin Pre-School molestation case brought widely 
divergent reactions.  The defendants wept with relief.  Parents of former students decried 
the system for failing their children.  Special targets of criticism were the personal 
ambitions of the prosecutors and the decision to have a private child-therapy group 
interview potential victims.  Jurors said they were not convinced beyond a reasonable 
doubt and never got the children's stories in their own words.  The case was the longest 
and most costly in American judicial history.  The lurid story at times included 
allegations of hundreds of molestations by seven individuals, underground tunnels, and 
Satanic rituals.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d080"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP900118-0190"
SELECTOR="A"
SUMMARIZER="I">

Seven jurors in the McMartin Pre-School molestation case talked with reporters after 
their acquittal of Raymond Buckey and his mother on Thursday.  The jurors faulted the 
videotaped interviews with the children, saying the interviewers asked leading questions 
so the children could not tell their own story.  The jurors also criticized a letter sent to 
parents by police after the first accusation, saying the letter put information out too early 
and led parents.  The jurors said even if some of the children had been molested, it was 
not proven that it happened at the school.  The trial took an enormous toll on everyone.</SUM> 

<SUM
