Neighbors of the McMartin Pre-School reacted today to the conclusion of the molestation 
trial against former teachers Raymond Buckey and his mother, Peggy McMartin Buckey, 
who were acquitted of 52 charges on Thursday.  Residents of the upper-middle-class 
suburb agreed the case poisoned everyone associated with it.  Sue Brown was convinced 
they were guilty.  Alan Lagunoff, whose son testified, was disappointed in both sides.  He 
would like the deserted, rundown, school to become a center for abused children.  Brenda 
Platt would like it torn down and considered the case a disgrace.  Linda Geisert was 
disappointed in the legal system and the jurors.</SUM>  

<SUM
DOCSET="d080"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA012190-0194"
SELECTOR="A"
SUMMARIZER="I">

The story of the McMartin Pre-School molestation case appears headed for television and 
the bookstores.  Screenwriter and producer Abby Mann became interested in the theme--
the hysteria of a witch hunt--in 1986 and allied with both the prosecution and the defense.  
He and his wife have a manuscript and screenplay in the works.  Two other books are 
planned.  Others also see "movie of the week" potential.  The networks, however, may 
not be willing to run the lurid tale because of ambiguities created by the jury's deadlock 
on 13 of the charges.  Child abuse and molestation already have become a more visible 
Hollywood theme.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d080"
