Who is to blame for the nation's longest and costliest trial, the McMartin Pre-School 
molestation case, which ended Thursday?  Raymond Buckey and his mother were 
acquitted on 52 counts and the jury deadlocked on the remaining 13.  Parents are blaming 
the system.  The original prosecutor, Robert Philibosian, denies he began the case to 
boost his run for district attorney and blames Ira Reiner, the current district attorney.  
Philibosian said Reiner hurt the case by dismissing charges against five defendants.  
Reiner claims he inherited a mess.  Many jurors believe some of the children were 
molested, but the state did not prove the defendants responsible.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d080"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA012090-0110"
SELECTOR="A"
SUMMARIZER="I">

Although the longest criminal trial in history is over, a baffling array of civil suits may 
follow the McMartin Pre-School molestation case.  One defendant is suing her accusers 
and her son may follow suit.  Parents may file suits on behalf of their children, because 
the burden of proof is less in a civil litigation.  No decisions have yet been made and 
there are doubts that any money would be available if anyone should win.  Two related 
cases are underway.  In one, early defendants are suing those who broke the story and, in 
another, defendants and the pre-school are suing liability insurance carriers.</SUM>

<SUM
